"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[9544],{49544:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"The Recovery Layer defines RTO (Recovery Time Objective) and RPO (Recovery Point Objective). The spec sets payments at RTO < 5 minutes, RPO = 0. What do these values mean and why is RPO = 0 non-negotiable for payment systems?","options":["RTO is the max acceptable data loss; RPO is the time to restore. Both being near-zero means no downtime or data loss is tolerated","RTO is the maximum time the system can be unavailable before unacceptable business impact; RPO is the maximum acceptable data loss. Payments set RPO=0 because losing even one transaction record creates financial liability — the database must reflect every committed payment, so synchronous replication with zero lag is required","RTO and RPO are the same metric — RTO measures downtime in minutes, RPO measures data loss in seconds","RTO applies to hardware failures; RPO applies to software bugs and deployment mistakes"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents RTO/RPO examples: Payment (RTO <5min, RPO 0), Core API (RTO <30min, RPO <5min), Analytics (RTO <24h, RPO <24h). RPO=0 means zero data loss — the backup must contain every committed transaction. For payments: a 5-minute data loss means 5 minutes of transactions are gone — customers were charged, money moved, but records don\'t exist. Legal liability, regulatory penalties, manual reconciliation at scale. RPO=0 requires synchronous replication (transaction commits on both primary AND replica before acknowledging). The spec uses Aurora Global Database for this.","hint":"RTO = \'how long can we be down?\' RPO = \'how much data can we afford to lose?\' Why would losing even ONE payment transaction be a serious problem?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Recovery Layer\'s Circuit Breaker diagram shows three states: Closed (normal), Open (blocking), and Half-Open (testing). What exactly happens in the Half-Open state?","options":["Half-Open rejects all requests and flushes the retry queue before transitioning to fully open","Half-Open allows ONE test request through to the failing dependency. If it succeeds, the circuit transitions back to Closed (normal operation resumes). If it fails, the circuit returns to Open (blocking continues) — this prevents hammering a recovering service while enabling automatic recovery detection","Half-Open serves stale cached responses for all requests while the circuit probes the service in the background","Half-Open is a 5-minute timeout state that prevents any requests regardless of service health"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents circuit breaker with `errorThresholdPercentage: 50` and `resetTimeout: 30000ms`. State machine: Closed (normal) → Open when error rate > 50% → after resetTimeout (30s), moves to Half-Open → sends ONE probe request → success: return to Closed; failure: back to Open. This solves the \'cascading failure\' problem: without circuit breakers, a slow downstream service causes all upstream threads to pile up waiting for timeouts, exhausting the thread pool. With circuit breakers, Open state fails fast — the upstream service stays responsive and the downstream gets time to recover.","hint":"The circuit can\'t stay Open forever — it needs a way to detect when the downstream service has recovered. How does Half-Open serve as that detection mechanism?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"Your team runs this script every night and considers backups verified. What critical flaw means your backups may be worthless?","code":"// Nightly backup verification job\\nasync function verifyNightlyBackup() {\\n  const backup = await s3.getObject({\\n    Bucket: \'prod-backups\',\\n    Key: `database-${today()}.sql.gz`,\\n  });\\n  \\n  if (backup.ContentLength && backup.ContentLength > 1_000_000) {\\n    console.log(`✓ Backup verified: ${backup.ContentLength} bytes`);\\n    await metrics.increment(\'backup.verified\');\\n    return true;\\n  }\\n  \\n  throw new Error(\'Backup too small or missing\');\\n}","codeLanguage":"typescript","options":["The backup file should be encrypted with AES-256 before uploading to S3","`ContentLength > 1_000_000` only verifies the file exists and is larger than 1MB — it does NOT verify the backup can be RESTORED. A corrupt pg_dump, truncated file, or schema mismatch passes this check. Real verification requires: download backup, decompress, restore to a test database, run integrity queries, confirm row counts match production","The script should use AWS Glacier instead of S3 for backup storage to reduce costs","The backup verification should run hourly, not nightly, to ensure RPO compliance"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec emphasizes: \'Backup restore tested quarterly\' and the principle that \'an untested backup is not a backup — it\'s an assumption.\' The spec documents the test restoration process: (1) Download backup from S3, (2) Restore to an isolated test RDS instance, (3) Run validation queries: `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM critical_tables`, (4) Compare row counts against production baseline, (5) Verify no foreign key violations. ContentLength > 1MB only confirms the file exists. A backup can be large but contain: corrupt data pages, a failed mid-dump snapshot, wrong schema version, missing tables.","hint":"A backup file that is 500MB but contains corrupt data will pass a size check. What\'s the only way to truly verify a backup works?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"According to the 13-layer architecture spec, if Layer 3 (Database) experiences a complete failure, describe the correct sequence of automated responses from Layer 12 (Monitoring) and Layer 13 (Recovery).","options":["Layer 12 logs the errors silently for 5 minutes to filter noise, then Layer 13 waits for a manual runbook execution by the on-call engineer","Layer 12 immediately detects the error rate spike and latency increase on database-dependent endpoints, fires P1 alerts to on-call, updates the status page, and triggers database-specific runbooks; Layer 13 activates automated failover to the Multi-AZ standby (10–60s), circuit breakers open on dependent services to prevent cascade failures, and health checks remove the failed database from the rotation","Layer 13 reboots the database pods while Layer 12 suppresses alerting during the reboot window to avoid noise","Layer 12 and 13 act independently — Layer 12 alerts human operators while Layer 13 waits for manual trigger of the DR runbook"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents an integrated response: Layer 12 instruments database connection errors and query latency as metrics. When DB fails: (1) Error rate hits alert threshold (2-minute evaluation window), (2) P1 alert fires to on-call rotation, (3) Status page auto-updates (Statuspage.io integration). Simultaneously, Layer 13: (1) Route53 health checks detect the primary DB endpoint failure, (2) Multi-AZ automatic failover promotes standby (10–60s), (3) Circuit breakers on the API layer open immediately (fail-fast), preventing thread exhaustion while DB is recovering. The spec requires all alerts to have runbooks.","hint":"What should Layer 12 detect first? What automated mechanism in Layer 13 handles DB promotion? What prevents the rest of the system from cascading while DB recovers?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Recovery Production Checklist, how frequently should Disaster Recovery plans and backup restoration be tested, and why does the spec emphasize testing over documentation?","options":["Annually — DR plans are stable documents that only need testing after major infrastructure changes","Monthly — financial regulations require monthly DR testing for all production payment systems","Quarterly — an untested DR plan is a false sense of security. The spec\'s principle: \'A backup that has never been restored is not a backup.\' Quarterly testing catches bit rot, process gaps, outdated runbooks, and ensures the team can execute the procedure under pressure before an actual incident","Weekly — each of the 13 layers should be tested on a rotating weekly schedule"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec explicitly states: \'Chaos experiments quarterly\' and \'Backup restore tested quarterly.\' The spec\'s reasoning: (1) Runbooks go stale — infrastructure changes and the documented steps no longer work, (2) Bit rot — backup files become unrestorable due to format changes, software version mismatches, or storage corruption, (3) Team capability — under a real incident at 3am, engineers who have never practiced the restore procedure take 3-5x longer. The spec also requires: \'Post-mortem template\' and \'Blameless post-mortems practiced\' within 48 hours of any incident.","hint":"A runbook written 6 months ago and never tested: what are the chances it still works after 3 infrastructure changes, a database version upgrade, and two team members leaving?"}]')}}]);